{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b4ff428d-a7dc-44e1-b54f-0348ac95944f","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing PerfView or ETW setup.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Need OS-level + .NET combined ETW traces |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check before tracing (e.g., `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Deep kernel + user-mode analysis |\n\n### Tip\nRun `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm CPU is actually in your managed code vs. native/GC — it'll save you time before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dc4f9cf9-4915-47f3-87cf-2221ffb8b8ec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":357},"id":"40a51952-308d-4594-bc98-4643ff50dfb9","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:51:38.870Z","parentId":"2bc4fad2-b593-449e-a150-89eef9a65233"}
